For each of the {= topic_category =} board-governance topic categories listed below, cover {= content_artifact =}+ distinct public content artifacts or tool surfaces. Each artifact is named by publisher and artifact title, classified by artifact format in `answer`, and supported by a public source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL) that proves the artifact's identity/content, access state, and scope/currentness state together.

The artifact is the publisher-controlled public resource surface itself. It is not an organization, a vendor product in the abstract, a search result, a topic keyword, a section heading, an access-status label, or a loose alias for a broad page. In-scope publishers include board portals, board-management vendors, nonprofit governance organizations, board associations, consultants, and governance assessment or governance-tool providers. The task is descriptive: source-backed evidence of what public artifacts show, not vendor ranking, product recommendation, white-space analysis, legal advice, contact collection, private-login inspection, or reproduction of full templates.

Topic categories:
- `roles_responsibilities`: board member, officer, committee, chair, director, staff-board, or fiduciary roles and responsibilities.
- `board_structure_composition`: board structure, board composition, board skills/composition matrices, recruitment/succession composition, or committee/member structure.
- `committee_charters`: committee charters, committee terms of reference, committee duties, committee mandate templates, or committee-governance guides.
- `board_assessment_evaluation`: board self-assessment, board evaluation, board effectiveness, skills assessment, performance review, survey, quiz, questionnaire, or improvement-planning resources.

Artifact formats:
- `downloadable_template`: a template, checklist, matrix, workbook, charter, policy, or comparable board-governance artifact offered as a download or file-delivery resource, including direct public PDFs/DOCs and visible form-gated delivery pages.
- `article_or_guide`: a public article, guide, PDF guide, explainer, or written resource with substantive board-governance content. It must function as a standalone governance resource, not merely an SEO summary, vendor feature page, or generic blog post with incidental board terminology.
- `interactive_builder_configurator`: a public builder, configurator, generator, wizard, calculator, or comparable workflow where visible user choices or steps shape the output or workflow. Product feature pages and demo CTAs do not count unless the public page itself exposes a usable public workflow or a clearly described public artifact.
- `assessment_quiz_survey_tool`: an assessment, quiz, questionnaire, survey, scoring tool, or administered assessment surface that captures board responses and returns or supports results, scores, reports, recommendations, or action plans. A static PDF questionnaire normally belongs under `downloadable_template` or `article_or_guide` unless the page is primarily presenting an assessment service/tool.
- `resource_library_collection`: a publisher-owned resource hub, topic page, library, or collection page that visibly gathers multiple board-governance resources, templates, tools, guides, or downloads under the submitted topic. A broad publisher hub is one collection artifact at most; do not resubmit the same hub under several topic/title variants unless the source exposes distinct topic-centered collection surfaces.

The artifact format is a source-backed classification claim, not a per-topic quota. Do not force sparse tool or assessment labels onto static articles, product feature pages, demo CTAs, generic AI generators, or template mills. Use the topic that the artifact primarily addresses; a broad library or guide should not be repeated under several topics unless the submitted artifact surface itself is a distinct topic-centered collection. Alias/title variants, source-hub titles, section headings, and access or currentness observations do not create new artifacts.

Valid sources are first-party publisher pages, official public PDFs or file landing pages, public resource libraries/topic pages, public tool/template pages, public form or registration pages that identify the artifact, and official help/docs when the claim is about a visible public surface. Generic template mills, search snippets, broad web-result pages, copied document mirrors, vendor rankings/listicles, unrelated "interactive" pages, generic team-role templates, and private portal/login-only content do not count. Broad publisher home pages, search pages, and resource hubs may support a submitted collection artifact, but they cannot stand in for many separate child artifacts unless they visibly identify each child as a distinct publisher-controlled artifact.

Requirements:
- The page must bind the submitted artifact to the submitted publisher and artifact title, either by directly identifying the artifact/resource or by visibly serving as the publisher-controlled artifact, library, tool, file, or access surface for it. A loose publisher alias, shortened title, topic label, section heading, or repeated source URL is not enough to create a separate artifact.
- The page must show the artifact's board-governance topic, claimed artifact format, and substantive content or tool character. Generic team, meeting, project-management, vendor-demo, or product-capability material does not satisfy this requirement unless the source visibly anchors the artifact in board governance as meant by the selected topic.
- The page must visibly support the artifact's access or gating state, such as direct public full-page access, direct file/download access, email/form-gated delivery, public registration, administered service, member-only access, paid/purchase access, unclear access, or conflicting access language. The state must be an observable property of the submitted artifact surface, not a guess from search-result availability.
- The page must visibly support the jurisdiction/geography state if one is stated, a source-backed not-stated/unclear state when the relevant artifact surface is specific enough to make absence auditable, and a date/currentness/copyright/update state or source-backed uncertainty/conflict. Do not infer artifact currentness from an unrelated site footer, unrelated sidebar date, URL filename alone, or silence on a broad page whose relevant scope/currentness context has not been inspected.
